<br>
This is an Big Dumb Booster type Heavy Lifter That I designed today.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Note - This image is mostly to scale, however, The payload fairing is a bit short.  Also, I made no attempt to scale the engines correctly.  They will probably have to be enlarged somewhat.  I'll do that when I have the time.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www4.ncsu.edu/unity/users/e/ejharman/www/ELIsCoolBDB-HLV.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Disclaimer - most of the features of this vehicle are &quot;borrowed&quot; from various designs I have encountered over the years. Please don't bitch at me for stealing your ideas.  If I ever turn this into an academic paper, you can be assured that all credit will be given where it is due. However, this is currently just my own thought process manifesting itself publicly.  Given that, I am too lazy to go back and find the originators of all the technologies and concepts involved.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
This is a classic BDB.  The fuel is kerosene and LOX, not the highest performance stuff from a specific impulse perspective, but cheap, easy to handle and has a high energy density.  The spherical fuel tanks facilitate the use of pressure fed engines by allowing the tanks to withstand a higher internal pressure per mass unit.  <br>
<br>
The engines utilize ablative cooling. A protective liner, similar to the FastTrac's, disintegrates and removes excess heat.  The bottom half of each spherical tanks also provide a sort of &quot;aeroplug&quot; nozzle effect for the ring of 24 engines surrounding each tank approximately at the equator. <br>
<br>
The bottom hemisphere of each tank is cooled by propellent flowing through pipes from the intake at the &quot;south pole&quot; to each engine. Steering is accomplished by differential throttling.  <br>
<br>
Each fuel tank is nested inside its oxidizer tank for the sake of compactness. This was how the tanks on the two upper stages of the Saturn V were arranged (yes I know the Saturn had this vice versa.)<br>
<br>
The payload fairing is 25m long by 11m in diameter.  It can accomodate 150 metric tonnes of cargo.<br>
<br>
The second stage has a dry mass of 37.5 tonnes, of which about 4 tonnes is the mass of the engines.  This assumption is based on data for the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/engines/rd0245hc.htm">RD-0245-HC.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
The upper stage outer tank has a diameter of 10.2m, giving a total capacity of 562.5 tonnes of LOX/Kero bi-propellent.<br>
<br>
This gives it a total mass of 750 tonnes and a mass ratio of 4/1<br>
<br>
The first stage has a dry mass of 187.5 tonnes, of which about 30 tonnes are engine mass.  This assumption is based on data from the <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/engines/nk33.htm">NK-33.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  This leaves 157.5 tonnes for structure.  <br>
<br>
The diameter of the outer fuel sphere is 17.4m, giving the first stage the capacity to hold 2814.5 tonnes of LOX/Kero bipropellent.  <br>
<br>
When taken with the 187.5 tonnes of dry mass and the 750 tonnes of the  upper-stage/payload, this gives the first stage a mass ratio of 4/1 as well.<br>
<br>
With a mass ratio of 4/1 and an ISP of 340 sec, each stage can achieve a Delta V of about 4.7km/sec, for a combined total of around 9.4km/sec.<br>
<br>
Given losses due to gravity and drag, this should be enough to reach low orbit.<br>
<br>
I would appreciate your comments/analysis regarding this design, mostly with regard to structural masses and potential costs.  <br>
<br>
Also, what effect would mass-production have on unit cost?  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A> at: 3/3/03 1:32:27 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 3:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=191.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Here Is an BDB HLV I Designed - Would Appreciate Comment</span><hr size=1> 1. Your design reminds me of the Russian/Soviet<br>
  N-1 booster that was designed by Chemoleai.<br>
2. Two 4/1 mass ratio stages with a 300 second<br>
 specific impulse will give an orbital injection velocity<br>
