This is true to an extent.  While higher ISP fuels like LH2 can allow one to reach orbital velocity with lower mass ratios, these mass ratios can be harder to attain because of hydrogen's bulkyness (what is the opposite of density?) and the resultant increase in tank size and weight.  You will probably notice the relatively small size of the fuel tanks in the above illustration.  I was surprised when I did the math and got such small fuel tanks to loft such a large payload fairing.  A rocket of this kind of campactness, and therefore, dry weight, would be impossible with LOX/LH2.  While my gross mass is higher than a crygenic-fueled booster, the dry mass is actually lower.  And dry mass is the stuff that has to be fabricated.  For any propellent used, fuel is the cheapest part of a launch. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A> at: 3/3/03 4:27:24 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 7:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=191.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   BDB</span><hr size=1> Are you sure about having such a large number of engines on the 1st and 2nd stages? I'm sure a Russian N-1 engineer would say &quot;nyet nyet!&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 8: