<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Are you sure about having such a large number of engines on the 1st and 2nd stages? I'm sure a Russian N-1 engineer would say &quot;nyet nyet!&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The cost of engine development increases exponentialy with thrust.  Using smaller engines should cut down on development costs.  <br>
<br>
The main drawback with having lots of engines is that there are more engines that can break.<br>
<br>
However, since this is a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Big Dumb Booster(TM)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the engines will be ultra simple.  Instead of having turbo pumps, they will be pressure fed. Instead of being regeneratively cooled, they will have ablative liners.  Instead of gimbling the engines for steering, the large number of them will permit differential throttleing to do the job. The number of components in each engine will be around two orders of magnitude lower than something like the shuttle engine.  <br>
<br>
TRW undertook the development of such a brutaly simple engine design back in the 60's, here are some excerpts from the article I read about their attempt.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>TRW farmed-out the fabrication of the engine and its supporting structure, less the injector that they fabricated themselves, to a &quot;job-shop&quot; commercial steel fabricator located near their facility . The contract price was $8000. Two TRW executives visited the facility to observe the fabrication process. They found only one individual working on the hardware, and when queried, he did not know nor care that he was building an aerospace rocket engine.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This was for an engine delivering over 1 million Newtons of thrust.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I had arrived late to witness the test, and only saw the firing. I was told by others who witnessed the entire test procedure that the engine was pulled out of outdoor storage where it lay unprotected against the elements. Before it was placed on the launch stand, the test crew dusted off the desert sand that had clung to it. This unplanned inlcusion of a bit of an environmental test also demonstrated hardware ruggedness of the kind no other liquid rocket eingine could approach.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
With this kind of simplicity comes not only economy but reliability.  A relatively large number of engines also provides redundancy and therefore additional safety.  <br>
<br>
This sort of clustering is not unprecedented. The Soyuz lifts off under the thrust of no less than 32 engines (20 main engines and 12 manuevering verniers) and has a history of almost 1700 successful missions. <br>
