A single thrust chamber would be simpler, but would be too large to gimble and would provide no differential throttling ability.  My design doesen't need as much thrust vectoring as most boosters, because the wide, flaring base makes it aerodynamically stable, much like a badmitton birdie.  However, it does still need to steer.  A single thurst chamber would need to have auxialiary manuvering verniers, so I don't know exactly how much complexity that appraoch would shave off.  Still, it probably bears further investigation.<br>
<br>
Another thing I like about using the base of the tank as an aerospike is that frame, tankage and engine are integrated into one structure, economizing on mass. The aerospike also gives the engines a variable expansion ratio, improving efficiency across the wide range of atmoshperic pressures at which they will operate.  From what I understand, that is the primary advantage of any aerospike engine.<br>
